The Steinhoff logo. JOHANNESBURG - The Financial Sector Conduct Authority is fining Steinhoff R53-million for making "false, misleading or deceptive statements" to the market. The fine comes after Steinhoff revealed accounting fraud in December 2017 that shocked investors and wiped more than R200-billion off its stock market value. READ:Â Naspers European tech company has stunning debut The company said the penalty would have been R1.5-billion, but was reduced because former employees perpetrated the fraud, and that the company had cooperated with regulators.